The office was quiet as I prepared for the afternoon. My manager, a Boomer who places a high value on physical presence in the office, had just left for a meeting. As a Gen Xer, I often find myself acting as a mediator between the old guard and the new waves of talent.

During my break, I received a call from my older daughter. She is a Millennial who recently started managing a small team of her own. She sounded frustrated. "Dad, my new intern is so self-centered," she complained. "He asked if he could get off work early just because he finished his specific tasks, without asking if anyone else needed help!" I chuckled, recognizing the generation gap. While she perceives this as a lack of teamwork, the intern likely sees it as a reward for efficiency. I explained to her that this disconnect often stems from different views on workplace loyalty.

Later, I had to deal with a small logistics issue in the hallway. A shipment of office supplies had been left right in the middle of the corridor. I watched a group of Gen Z interns walk around it, unsure of whose job it was to move it. I stepped in and made sure the boxes got out of the way so our Silent Generation consultant could walk through safely. Generally speaking, my role is to ensure these small frictions don't turn into major problems.

By the time I was ready to get off work, I realized that everyone‚Äîfrom my self-centered intern-frustrated daughter to the quiet consultant‚Äîis just trying to navigate their own version of a career. By and large, we all want to be productive; we just have very different ways of showing it.
